ground_truth_answer: Subcontractors must meet non-discrimination and drug-free workplace requirements. During bidding (Excerpt 1, 1.4.B), the Engineer must evaluate subcontractor acceptability. (Section 2.B.1) mandates that subcontracts over $10,000 include clauses prohibiting discrimination and requiring drug-free workplaces.

llm_response: The Project Manager has the authority to require the removal of a subcontractor.
ground_truth_answer: The Project Manager may require the removal of a subcontractor.

llm_response: The SCC registration option that applies is: "An out-of-state business entity that does not regularly and continuously maintain as part of its ordinary and customary business any employees, agents, offices, facilities, or inventories in Virginia."
ground_truth_answer: The entity must not regularly maintain employees, offices, or facilities in Virginia, excluding incidental presence for assembly/repair or solicitation of orders requiring out-of-state acceptance.

llm_response: By signing the Proposal Signature Sheet, the Offeror certifies that the proposal complies with all RFP requirements, the Offeror hasn't engaged in any actions that restrain free, competitive bidding, and the signer is authorized to sign as a legal representative of the business entity.
ground_truth_answer: The signature certifies compliance with the RFP requirements and confirms no collusion or antitrust violations occurred during proposal preparation.

llm_response: A Contractor must formally dispute a County decision on a claim by providing written notice of their intention to file a claim or dispute within fifteen (15) days after the event on which the claim is based. Additionally, if the Contractor disagrees with the County's decision, they must notify the County in writing that they are proceeding with the work under protest. If the dispute is unresolved, the Contractor can appeal the County's decision within six months by instituting legal action in the appropriate circuit court.
ground_truth_answer: The Contractor must notify the County in writing that they are proceeding with the work under protest.

llm_response: Subcontractor payment obligations are enforced under the contract by requiring the Contractor to: (A) pay any subcontractor its proportionate share of the payment received within seven days or notify about withholding payment and the reason; (B) provide necessary identification numbers before payment; (C) pay interest on overdue amounts not withheld for valid reasons; and (D) include these requirements in contracts with subcontractors. Compliance with antitrust laws is ensured by the Contractor's certifications that the bid is competitive and free from
ground_truth_answer: Contractors must pay subcontractors within seven days of receiving County payments or provide written justification for withholding (Section 12). Subcontracts must include these terms. The Proposal Signature Sheet (Section 2) certifies compliance with the Sherman Act and Virginia antitrust laws, prohibiting collusion in bidding.

llm_response: The County can terminate the contract for default if any of the following events occur: (a) the Contractor fails to deliver the equipment or services required by the contract, (b) the Contractor repeatedly fails to respond to requests for maintenance or other services within the time limits set forth in the contract, or (c) the Contractor breaches any terms of the contract and fails to cure the failure/nonperformance within ten days after receiving a "Show Cause Notice" from the County.
ground_truth_answer: The County may terminate the contract for default if the Contractor fails to deliver equipment/services, repeatedly fails to respond to maintenance requests, or breaches other terms after a "Show Cause Notice."

ground_truth_answer: Six (6) copies of the proposal are requested.

llm_response: The Owner and Architect waive all rights against each other and against their contractors, consultants, agents, and employees for damages covered by property insurance.
ground_truth_answer: The Owner and Architect waive all rights against each other and against contractors, consultants, agents, and employees for damages covered by property insurance, except rights to insurance proceeds.

llm_response: Engineering firms must perform tasks in accordance with generally accepted professional standards and comply with regulations, laws, ordinances, and requirements of all governmental agencies and authorities with jurisdiction over design criteria and environmental impact applicable to the services provided. Additionally, all designs must conform to the latest County, state, and federal regulations or standards, including erosion control and sedimentation rules, regulations, and ordinances.
ground_truth_answer: Firms must comply with all federal, state, and local laws, ordinances, and regulations, including environmental and procurement laws. (Section 1.1) requires adherence to "regulations, laws, ordinances, and requirements of all governmental agencies," while (Exhibit A, Section 2.C) mandates conformity with the Civil Rights Act, Virginia Fair Employment Contracting Act, and Immigration Reform and Control Act.

llm_response: The recycling center's main building must be a 40 x 60 enclosed blue metal building with a 20 x 60 lean-to structure. It requires 6x6 timber posts with in-ground protectors spaced at 12’ on center, steel trusses, and 29-gauge metal sides. The building should have two 10’ wide x 12’ tall drum roll-up doors, two pedestrian access doors, one exterior window, be insulated, include an interior office framed and finished
ground_truth_answer: The main building requires a 40x60 enclosed blue metal structure with a 20x60 lean-to.

llm_response: The deadline for project completion is September 30th, 2025.
ground_truth_answer: The project must be completed by September 30th, 2025.

ground_truth_answer: Compensation for Basic Services is based on a stipulated sum allocated across defined project phases.

llm_response: Insufficient information to answer question based on given context.
ground_truth_answer: Past performance (Excerpt 1, Section 5) is evaluated for quality, timeliness, and budget adherence, which directly impacts the County's right to terminate for default (Excerpt 2, Section 16) if contractors fail to meet obligations.

llm_response: The contractor must provide: (1) build scripts, (2) build environment details, (3) patch installer creation instructions, (4) build logs, (5) build tools with associated configurations, and (6) integrated development environment (IDE) details associated with loading, reading, modifying, and building source code documents.
ground_truth_answer: The Contractor shall provide all materials necessary to build the source code into an executable and functioning application, including build scripts, build environment details, patch installer creation instructions, build logs, build tools with configurations, and integrated development environment (IDE) details.

llm_response: The inclusion of proprietary or limited data rights will not be acceptable; the AFATDS 7.0 software baseline must have Government unlimited data rights.
ground_truth_answer: Proprietary data, code, or products are strictly prohibited in the AFATDS baseline, except for free and open-source software (FOSS).

llm_response: Contractor employees with security clearances must complete annual Threat Awareness and Reporting Program (TARP) training.
ground_truth_answer: Annual Threat Awareness and Reporting Program (TARP) training is required, with certifications submitted to the COR.

llm_response: The processes and practices employed to ensure that genuine information and communications technology (ICT) will be used in the solution, and that these processes and requirements for genuine ICT are imposed on subcontractors.
ground_truth_answer: Processes must verify genuine ICT and enforce requirements on subcontractors.

llm_response: U.S. SECRET clearance from the Defense Security Service is required for access to the AFATDS software baseline.
ground_truth_answer: Contractors must have a U.S. SECRET facility clearance from the Defense Security Service.

llm_response: Distribution restrictions for unclassified technical data under Block 9 are that it is export-controlled and subject to the provisions of DoD Directive 5230.25.
ground_truth_answer: Unclassified data is export-controlled and subject to DoD Directive 5230.25, with distribution limited to DoD agencies and U.S. DoD contractors.

llm_response: Subcontractors must use the DoD-approved XML format for IPMR submissions.
ground_truth_answer: Subcontractors must use the DoD-approved XML format.

llm_response: The contractor must conduct a review for evidence of compromise, identify compromised systems and data, analyze affected networks, and rapidly report the cyber incident to DoD at http://dibnet.dod.mil.
ground_truth_answer: The contractor must conduct a review for compromised data, systems, and user accounts, and rapidly report the incident to DoD via the specified portal.

llm_response: If the Contractor modifies the Interface Control Document after Government approval, they must resubmit it for Government review and approval.
ground_truth_answer: The Contractor must resubmit the revised document for Government review and approval. The Government will provide comments within 30 calendar days of receipt, and the final version is due back within 30 days after receiving comments.

llm_response: The Contractor shall deliver 45 calendar days after contract award.
ground_truth_answer: The Contractor shall deliver 90 calendar days after award of contract. The Contractor shall deliver 30 calendar days prior to contract expiration.

ground_truth_answer: The subtasks are Integration Management Control Planning (Subtask 1) and Task Order Management (Subtask 2).

llm_response: The contractor forfeits the flat fee bonus for Gates 1–3 if the Government decides to assume greater risk and accept a delinquent AFATDS v7.0 final release under the final gate of Incentive #2.
ground_truth_answer: The contractor forfeits the flat fee bonus if they do not successively pass Gates 1, 2, and 3. This does not affect their eligibility for the Final Gate fee.

llm_response: Contractors must conduct activities in accordance with applicable laws and regulations on the interception, monitoring, access, use, and disclosure of electronic communications and data.
ground_truth_answer: Contractors must comply with applicable laws and regulations on interception, monitoring, access, use, and disclosure of electronic communications and data.

llm_response: Subtask 3 requires AFATDS 7.0 to maximize the use of common services from the COE environment, allowing developers to focus on developing fires capabilities and integration tasks associated with accessing external services.

llm_response: Unrealistically low or high proposed costs may lead to the elimination of a proposal from competition, either because it indicates that the offeror does not understand the requirement or because the proposal is unrealistic.
ground_truth_answer: Unrealistically low or high proposed costs may result in elimination from competition, as they indicate the offeror may not understand requirements or has submitted an unrealistic proposal. Unbalanced costs may also lead to rejection.

llm_response: The Contractor's System Safety Program Plan (SSPP) must include the tasks the Contractor will perform to fulfill the level of rigor activities and system and software safety analysis per MIL-STD-882E and the Joint Software System Safety Engineering handbook.
ground_truth_answer: The SSPP must include tasks to fulfill system and software safety analysis per MIL-STD-882E and the Joint Software System Safety Engineering Handbook.

llm_response: Final submissions for PM MC must be posted to DI2E and IDE with email notification to the Contracting Officer’s Representative.
ground_truth_answer: Submissions must be posted to DI2E and IDE with email notification to the Contracting Officer’s Representative.

llm_response: Access by foreign nationals to program information must be controlled through processes including, but not limited to, protecting system design information, DoD-unique technology, and software or hardware used to integrate commercial technology.
ground_truth_answer: Processes must control access to system design information, DoD-unique technology, and integration tools for commercial technology.

llm_response: The permitted uses of contractor attributional/proprietary information obtained by DoD include release outside of DoD to entities with missions potentially affected by such information, entities for assistance in cyber incident diagnosis, detection, or mitigation, government entities conducting counterintelligence or law enforcement investigations, national security purposes, and to support services contractors directly supporting government activities under specific contract clauses. Additionally, if created by or for DoD, such information may be used and released for other lawful government purposes and activities subject to applicable
ground_truth_answer: The information may be used and released outside DoD for purposes authorized by paragraph (i) of the clause and for any lawful Government purpose, subject to statutory, regulatory, and policy restrictions.

llm_response: MIL-STD-40051-1B and MIL-STD-40051-2B govern the development of Interactive Electronic Technical Manuals (IETMs).

llm_response: Part A - Summary of Relevant Past Performance Contracts, Part B - Subcontractor/Teaming Partner Consent Letters, Part C - Client Authorization Letters.
ground_truth_answer: The Past Performance volume must be organized into Part A (Summary of Relevant Past Performance Contracts), Part B (Subcontractor/Teaming Partner Consent Letters), and Part C (Client Authorization Letters).

llm_response: The contracting officer (KO), contracting officer's representative (COR), and/or designated representatives are authorized to access contractor records and facilities during service performance.
ground_truth_answer: The Contractor shall permit the contracting officer (KO), contracting officer's representative (COR), and/or designated representatives access at any reasonable time to all records, data, and facilities used in performance of the contemplated services.

llm_response: The primary objective of CLIN 0001 under this contract is to modernize the existing AFATDS software baseline to provide a modernized backend AFATDS architecture, incorporate Common Services provided by the Common Operating Environment v3, implement role duty-based functionality, and provide embedded computer-based training.
ground_truth_answer: CLIN 0001 requires modernizing the AFATDS software baseline to align with AFATDS v7.0 requirements, including backend architecture updates, Common Services integration, role-based functionality, and embedded training.

llm_response: The Government evaluates option periods for award purposes by adding the total price for all options to the total price for the base period. Offerors must submit pricing for the base period and all option periods, including pricing for an additional six-month extension period as authorized by FAR 52.217-8. The pricing for this additional six-month period should be identical to the pricing in the six months prior to the expiration of the base or final option period. The Government may find an offer unacceptable if the option prices
ground_truth_answer: Option pricing, including a six-month extension under FAR 52.217-8, is added to the base period price for evaluation.

llm_response: An Organizational Conflict of Interest (OCI) is defined as a situation where, due to other activities or relationships, a person is unable or potentially unable to render impartial assistance or advice to the Government, the person's objectivity in performing contract work is impaired, or a person has an unfair competitive advantage.
ground_truth_answer: An organizational conflict of interest occurs when a contractor’s other activities or relationships impair their ability to provide impartial advice, create an unfair competitive advantage, or compromise objectivity.
